On September 5, [[Caroline Wozniacki]] and [[Maria Sharapova]] became the first two players to qualify for the championships.<ref name="first qualifiers">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~2442223,00.html |title='Wozniacki, Sharapova, Peschke & Srebotnik Qualify' |publisher=Wtachampionships.com |date=2011-09-05 |accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref> 
[[File:Caroline Wozniacki at the 2011 Australian Open1 crop.jpg|thumb|150px|left|[[Caroline Wozniacki]] led the tour with a 62<U+2013>15 record in 2011]]

'''Caroline Wozniacki''' won six singles titles in 2011. She began the year with a loss at the [[2011 Medibank International Sydney|Medibank International Sydney]] to [[Dominika Cibulkov<U+00E1>]]. She then reached three consecutive finals at the [[2011 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai Tennis Championships]] deafeating [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]] 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>3, [[2011 Qatar Ladies Open|Qatar Ladies Open]] losing to [[Vera Zvonareva]] 4<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6, and [[2011 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]] beating [[Marion Bartoli]] 6<U+2013>1, 2<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3. Her 3rd title came at the [[2011 Family Circle Cup|Family Circle Cup]], where she won against unseeded [[Elena Vesnina]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3. She then lost to [[Julia G<U+00F6>rges]] 6<U+2013>7<sup>(3<U+2013>7)</sup>, 3<U+2013>6 at the [[2011 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Porsche Tennis Grand Prix]]. Her 4th and 5th singles title were at the [[2011 Brussels Open|Brussels Open]] defeating [[Peng Shuai]] 2<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>3, and her home tournament the [[2011 e-Boks Sony Ericsson Open|e-Boks Sony Ericsson Open]] defeating [[Lucie <U+0160>af<U+00E1><U+0159>ov<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>4. However, she had a 3-match losing streak in the summer season before winning the [[2011 New Haven Open at Yale|New Haven Open at Yale]] against [[Petra Cetkovsk<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>1 for the 4th consecutive time. At the Slams, Wozniacki reached the semis of the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]] and the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], falling to [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] 3<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5, 6<U+2013>3 after failing to convert a match point and [[Serena Williams]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>4  respectively. However, she suffered early exits in the third round of the [[2011 French Open|French Open]] to [[Daniela Hantuchov<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>3 and the fourth round of the [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] to [[Dominika Cibulkov<U+00E1>]] 1<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>5)</sup>, 7<U+2013>5. This is her third appearance at the event, with her best result in 2010 when she reached the final.

[[File:Maria Sharapova - Roland Garros 2011 (crop).jpg|170px|right|thumb|[[Maria Sharapova]] qualified for the fifth time]]
'''Maria Sharapova''' regained some of her form by performing consistently throughout the year with two Premier-5 titles. Sharapova was crowned [[2011 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Internazionali BNL d'Italia]] on red clay, by beating World no. 1 [[Caroline Wozniacki]] 7<U+2013>5, 6<U+2013>3 in the semis and sixth-seeded [[Samantha Stosur]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>4 in the final. Her second title came at the [[2011 Western & Southern Open|Western & Southern Open]], where she defeated fellow former World No. 1 [[Jelena Jankovi<U+0107>]] 4<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>3)</sup>, 6<U+2013>3 in two hours and 49 minutes, making it the longest WTA tour final this year. She also made 2 other finals at the [[2011 Sony Ericsson Open|Sony Ericsson Open]], losing to [[Victoria Azarenka]] 1<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6  and the final of the [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]], losing to [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] 3<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6. This was also her first Grand Slam final appearance since winning the [[2008 Australian Open]] . At the other Slams, Sharapova reached the Semifinals of the [[2011 French Open|French Open]], falling to eventual champion [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] 4<U+2013>6, 5<U+2013>7, but fell early in the fourth round of the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]], losing 2<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6 to [[Andrea Petkovic]], and the third round of the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], beaten by [[Flavia Pennetta]] 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, 4<U+2013>6. This is the first time since 2007 that she has been qualified for the Championships. She has never lost before the semifinals in her previous four appearances, with her best result on her debut at the event, beating [[Serena Williams]] in 2004. 

On October 1, [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] and [[Victoria Azarenka]] qualified for the championships.<ref name="second qualifiers">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~2469318,00.html |title='Four More WTA Stars Headed to Istanbul' |publisher=Wtachampionships.com |date=2011-10-01 |accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref>
[[File:Petra Kvitov<U+00E1> Roland Garros 2011.jpg|thumb|155px|left|[[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] became the first Slam champion born in the '90s]]

'''Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>''' won five titles prior to the Championships, capturing her sixth at this tournament. She began the year by winning the [[2011 Brisbane International|Brisbane International]], defeating [[Andrea Petkovic]] 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>3. She then reached a quarter-finals at the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]], upsetting 5th seed [[Samantha Stosur]] 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>5)</sup>, 6<U+2013>3 in the third round before losing to [[Vera Zvonareva]] 2<U+2013>6, 4<U+2013>6. She then won the [[2011 Open GDF Suez|Open GDF Suez]], defeating [[Kim Clijsters]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>3. She then lost 4 of her next 5 matches before winning the [[2011 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]] defeating [[Victoria Azarenka]] 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>3)</sup>, 6<U+2013>4 in the final. Later, she fell in the fourth round of the [[2011 French Open|French Open]] to eventual champion [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] 2<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>3. She then reached the final of the [[2011 Aegon International|Aegon International]], losing to [[Marion Bartoli]] 1<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>4, 5<U+2013>7. Her most significant title came by winning the [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] over [[Maria Sharapova]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>4 in the final. After the triumph, she lost back-to-back third round matches to [[Andrea Petkovic]] in the [[2011 US Open Series|US Open Series]] before becoming the first Wimbledon champion ever to fall in the first round of the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] to [[Alexandra Dulgheru]]  7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>3)</sup>, 6<U+2013>3. She then won her fifth title of the year at the [[2011 Generali Ladies Linz|Generali Ladies Linz]], defeating Slovakian [[Dominika Cibulkov<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>1. This is her debut at the championships.

[[File:Victoria Azarenka at the WTA Istanbul 2011 0010002 Nevit.jpg|thumb|145px|right|[[Victoria Azarenka]] reached a new career-high of world no. 3]]

'''Victoria Azarenka''' won three titles this year. She picked up her second [[2011 Sony Ericsson Open|Sony Ericsson Open]] trophy after defeating [[Maria Sharapova]] in the final 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>4 and upsetting 2nd seed [[Kim Clijsters]] and 3rd seed [[Vera Zvonareva]] earlier. She then won her first clay title the following week at the [[2011 Andalucia Tennis Experience|Andalucia Tennis Experience]], defeating [[Irina-Camelia Begu]] in the final 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>2. She then claimed a title before the championships at the [[2011 BGL Luxembourg Open|BGL Luxembourg Open]] defeating [[Monica Niculescu]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>2. She reached another final at the [[2011 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]], losing to [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] in the final 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>3)</sup>, 6<U+2013>4. Azarenka reached her first Slam semifinal at [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] losing to eventual champion [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>1, 3<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>2. At the other Slams, she lost in the fourth round of the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]] and the quarterfinal of the [[2011 French Open|French Open]] both to [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]], and the third round of the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|2011 US Open]] to [[Serena Williams]] 6<U+2013>1, 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>5)</sup>. Azarenka is making her third consecutive appearance at the event. 
    
[[File:French Open 2011 Li Na.jpg|left|135px|thumb|[[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] became the first Asian player to win a Grand Slam singles title]]
On October 5, [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] became the fifth player to qualify for the championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~2473548,00.html |title='Chinese Trailblazer Li Qualifies For Istanbul' |publisher=Wtachampionships.com |date=2011-10-05 |accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref>

'''Li Na''' has had a memorable yet very inconsistent year. She started the year by winning [[2011 Medibank International Sydney|Sydney]] defeating [[Kim Clijsters]] in the final 7<U+2013>6<sup>(3)</sup>, 6<U+2013>3 and reaching the final of the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]], upsetting world no. 1 [[Caroline Wozniacki]] in the semi-finals, but losing to [[Kim Clijsters]] 6<U+2013>3, 3<U+2013>6, 3<U+2013>6. However, she lost her next 4 matches before bouncing back in the European clay season, reaching the semifinals of the [[2011 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]] and [[2011 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Internazionali BNL d'Italia]]. Li then won her first Grand Slam title and became the first Grand Slam singles champion born in an Asian country at the [[2011 French Open|French Open]], defeating defending champion [[Francesca Schiavone]] 6<U+2013>4, 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>0)</sup> in the final. Following her French Open victory, she has had disappointing results for the rest of the year with the 5<U+2013>7 record, including the second round lost at [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] to [[Sabine Lisicki]] 6<U+2013>3, 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>8 and the first round defeat from [[Simona Halep]] 6<U+2013>2, 7<U+2013>5 at the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]]. Li is making her debut at the tournament after being an alternate last year.

[[File:Vera Zvonareva - 2009 US Open.jpg|right|150px|thumb|[[Vera Zvonareva]] reached the semifinals of Australian Open]] 
On October 9, [[Vera Zvonareva]] and [[Samantha Stosur]] qualified for the championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtachampionships.com/page/LatestNews/Read/0,,12910~2476824,00.html |title='Zvonareva & Stosur: Qualifiers No.6 & No.7' |publisher=Wtachampionships.com |date=2011-10-09 |accessdate=2011-10-30}}</ref>

'''Vera Zvonareva''' was not able to duplicate her 2010 season in 2011, however, she won two titles this year to one in the previous year. She won her first title in over a year at the [[2011 Qatar Ladies Open|Qatar Ladies Open]], defeating world no. 1 [[Caroline Wozniacki]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>4 in the final. She then won her second title at the [[2011 Baku Cup|Baku Cup]], beating her compatriot [[Ksenia Pervak]] in the final 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>4. She reached two other finals in the [[2011 Mercury Insurance Open|Mercury Insurance Open]] and the [[2011 Toray Pan Pacific Open]], both losing to [[Agnieszka Radwa<U+0144>ska]] with a scoreline of 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>4 and 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>2, respectively. At the Slams, her best result was reaching the semi-finals of the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]], losing to [[Kim Clijsters]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>3. She also lost in the quarterfinals of the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] to [[Samantha Stosur]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>3, the fourth round of the [[2011 French Open|French Open]] to [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]] 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>4)</sup>, 2<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>2, and the third round of the [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] to [[Tsvetana Pironkova]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3. Zvonareva is making her fifth appearance at the Championships. Her best result was reaching the final in 2008. 

[[File:Samantha Stosur at the 2010 US Open 07.jpg|left|150px|thumb|[[Samantha Stosur]] wins her first slam]] 

'''Samantha Stosur''' did not enjoy a successful first half of the year, failing to reach a semifinal of any event until the [[2011 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Porsche Tennis Grand Prix]] in April. She then reached her first final of the year at the [[2011 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Internazionali BNL d'Italia]], losing to [[Maria Sharapova]] 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>4, despite having not lost a set before the final. She reached her second final at the [[2011 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]] before falling to [[Serena Williams]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>2 in the final. In September, she became the winner of the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] after beating the heavy favorite [[Serena Williams]] in the final in straight sets 6<U+2013>2, 6<U+2013>3, to win her maiden Slam title. She also became the first Australian woman to win a Slam since [[Evonne Goolagong Cawley]] won Wimbledon in 1980. She then reached the final of the [[2011 HP Open|HP Open]] losing to [[Marion Bartoli]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>1. In the other Slams, she fell in the third rounds of the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]] to [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>5)</sup>, 6<U+2013>3 and [[2011 French Open|French Open]] to [[Gisela Dulko]] 6<U+2013>4, 1<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, and the first round of the [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] to 262nd ranked [[Melinda Czink]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>4. Stosur is making her second appearance at the event, after the semifinals' appearance in 2010. 
[[File:Fed Cup Group I 2011 Europe Africa day 4 Agnieszka Radwa<U+0144>ska 008.jpg|right|130px|thumb|[[Agnieszka Radwa<U+0144>ska]] qualified for the first time]]
On October 21, [[Agnieszka Radwa<U+0144>ska]] became the last to qualify after [[Marion Bartoli]] withdrew in her quarterfinal match in [[2011 Kremlin Cup|Kremlin Cup]]

'''Agnieszka Radwa<U+0144>ska''' reached three finals in 2011 and won all of them, thus ending her 3 year-title drought. Her first title of the year came in the [[2011 Mercury Insurance Open|Mercury Insurance Open]], where she defeated top seed [[Vera Zvonareva]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>4 in the final. In the Asian swing season, she won back-to-back titles in the [[2011 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]] over [[Vera Zvonareva]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>2 and the [[2011 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] over [[Andrea Petkovic]] 7<U+2013>5, 0<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>4, winning her biggest title so far. At the slams, Radwa<U+0144>ska was able to reach her fourth slam quarterfinal at the [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]] losing to eventual champion [[Kim Clijsters]] 6<U+2013>3, 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>4)</sup>. However, she fell short in the fourth round of the [[2011 French Open|French Open]] to [[Maria Sharapova]] 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>4)</sup>, 7<U+2013>5, the second rounds of both the [[2011 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] to [[Petra Cetkovsk<U+00E1>]] 3<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>6<sup>(7<U+2013>5)</sup>, 6<U+2013>4, and the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] to [[Angelique Kerber]] 6<U+2013>3, 4<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3. She is making her third appearance, having played as the alternate here in 2008 and 2009.  

The first alternate for the championships is Frenchwomen '''[[Marion Bartoli]]''', who has reached 5 finals in the year. She reached her first Premier Mandatory final at the [[2011 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]] losing to [[Caroline Wozniacki]] 6<U+2013>1, 2<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>3, then lost her next final at the [[2011 Internationaux de Strasbourg|Internationaux de Strasbourg]] to [[Andrea Petkovic]] retiring being down 6<U+2013>4, 1<U+2013>0. She then won her first title since 2009 at the [[2011 Aegon International|Aegon International]] defeating [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>1, 4<U+2013>6, 7<U+2013>5. At [[2011 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], she lost to [[Sabine Lisicki]] 6<U+2013>4, 6<U+2013>7<sup>(4<U+2013>7)</sup>, 6<U+2013>1 in the quarterfinal after upsetting [[Serena Williams]] in the previous round. On the contrary, she fell to [[Serena Williams]] in the final of the [[2011 Bank of the West Classic|Bank of the West Classic]]. She then won her second title of the year at the [[2011 HP Open]] defeating [[Samantha Stosur]] 6<U+2013>3, 6<U+2013>1 in the final. At the [[2011 French Open]], she reached her second career slam semifinal. The second alternate is '''[[Andrea Petkovic]]''', who is enjoying her best season so far by cracking the top 10. She won her lone title of the year at the [[2011 Internationaux de Strasbourg|Internationaux de Strasbourg]] over [[Marion Bartoli]]. She then reached two other final, at the [[2011 Brisbane International|Brisbane International]] losing to [[Petra Kvitov<U+00E1>]] 6<U+2013>1, 6<U+2013>3 and the final of the [[2011 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] losing to [[Agnieszka Radwa<U+0144>ska]] 7<U+2013>5, 0<U+2013>6, 6<U+2013>4 in her first Premier Mandatory final. At the slams she was able to reach the quarterfinals in 3 of the 4 majors excluding [[2011 Wimbledon|Wimbledon]].    
{{clear}}

